            <div class="page-header"><h1><span class="intertitre"><a name="up"></a></span>Amdo Tibetan</h1></div>
                
                <div class="text-left">
                <p class="intertitre">&nbsp;</p>

      <p class="intertitre"><a href="https://pangloss.cnrs.fr/corpus/show_text_en.php?id=cocoon-7d6235a0-7b5a-416d-8077-01eae61efd28&idref=cocoon-b1d1b067-16fd-47db-b3c5-60ed2dd45045"><img src="../images/icones/Txt_Inter_parchemin1.jpg" alt="a" width="30" height="30" border="0">Leisure and Tibetan game of Jacks (knucklebones)</a></p>
      
            <p>The main speaker, འབྲུག་མོ་ཡག, is a woman who was aged 38 as of 2017. She was born into a family of cattle breeders from སྤྱང་ལུང་།, in the county of Tsekhog. At the time of recording, she had been living for 12 years in the county seat of Rebkong (Chinese: Tongren 同仁县), which neighbours on Tsekhog and is the traditional cultural centre of the area. She did not attend school but she nonetheless managed to learn to read Written Tibetan. She is currently a nurse at the Tibetan medical hospital in Rebkong.<br/>
            Speaker #3 is her niece. She was born in Rebkong. She was 14 at the time of recording, and was a junior high school student. She can speak and write Tibetan and Chinese, as well as some English. <br/>
            Speaker #4 is her husband, རྡོ་རྗེ་བཀྲ་ཤིས།, a 40-year old man born in རྒྱལ་བོ་ཤང་།, a village close to the county seat of Rebkong. He attended school up to senior high school, and is a medical doctor at the Tibetan medical hospital in Rebkong. In addition to Tibetan, he speaks fluent Chinese.<br/>
            Speaker #2 is the visiting linguist.</p>

        

            <p><img src="../images/photos_pangloss/simon/2TIB_Jeux-REB2017-Osselets.jpg" width="300"><br/>
